## typed_page_sections_redesign

### Current Progress

- **Phase 1: Existing behavior inventory and contract fixtures** — ✅ Complete
- **Phase 2: Canonical schemas and typed registry** — ✅ Complete
- **Phase 3: Shared frontend section shell** — ✅ Complete
- **Phase 4: Shadow normalized persistence** — ✅ Complete
- **Phase 5: Typed APIs and concurrency cutover** — ✅ Complete
- **Phase 6: Sensitive-data and preset migration** — ✅ Complete
- **Phase 7: Cutover, rollback window, and cleanup** — ✅ Complete

### Completed Work (Phases 1-3)

- [x] Use `.routines/worker` to inventory all current section, item, and shared
      shell fields/defaults/legacy aliases in a checked-in compatibility matrix.
- [x] Include background/text/`h1`/`h2`/`h3` color sources, page palette tokens,
      content scale, and collapse settings in the first shared-shell schema;
      define permission-aware viewer state alongside it as ephemeral UI state.
- [x] Capture the existing REST/WebSocket/cache/SEO/reconnect/merge paths and
      freeze content-free page-update propagation with a regression test.
- [x] Add optimistic-revision acceptance tests before changing the persistence
      model; the expected same-section conflict and different-section convergence
      behavior now runs through the reusable fail-closed revision guard.
- [x] Collect the sanitized schema/config-shape inventory for `cueballcraft` and
      `thewriterco`; 2026-07-17 baseline is summarized in the plan and the raw
      production-content export remains uncommitted in local `output.txt`.
- [x] Confirm deployed legacy `page_sections` and `page_items` are empty in both
      current tenants; retain a transactional fail-closed emptiness preflight in
      the eventual rename/retirement migration.
- [x] Define the canonical mapping for object/string configs, `features` to
      `feature_grid`, page-scoped numeric/string legacy IDs, and empty visibility.
- [x] Derive minimal anonymized fixtures for every observed production shape;
      do not commit raw production page content.
- [x] Add representative legacy `pages.content` fixtures and no-loss
      parse/save/copy/duplicate, registry, shell-default, and alias tests.
- [x] Make renderer dispatch exhaustive across all canonical types, resolve the
      production `features` alias, and render a safe visible unknown-type fallback.
- [x] Add DOM parity tests for the simple-grid, hero-media, datasource-derived,
      and interactive renderer families before replacing the current block shells.
- [x] Establish JSON Schema 2020-12 as the canonical source format; add embedded
      page-theme/shared-shell v1 contracts and expose them through the registry API.
- [x] Add normalized item/preset and all 19 versioned section-config contracts;
      canonical interactive configs exclude runtime `records`/`result_summary`.
- [x] Bind registry config versions, defaults, capabilities, config schemas, and
      item schemas to the embedded contracts with exact drift tests.
- [x] Add fail-closed Draft 2020-12 runtime validation for every embedded
      normalized contract, including local `$ref`/default checks, bounded CSS
      colors, sanitized errors, and an explicit boundary from legacy validation.
- [x] Generate the frontend `SectionType`, `SectionConfigByType`, per-type config
      aliases, versions, defaults, and capabilities from backend contracts; add
      deterministic Go and npm drift checks and remove the handwritten type list.
- [x] Generate normalized Go discriminators/config DTOs and add a bounded,
      duplicate-key-safe decode factory that validates before typed decoding.
- [x] Introduce the generic normalized `PageSection<T>` frontend boundary and a
      compatibility adapter that separates shell/config/runtime data, retains
      numeric-or-string legacy keys, quarantines unknown input, and projects back
      to the current document envelope.

### Phase 2 Closure

Phase 2 ends at the generated, runtime-validated contract boundary. All 19
section configs, shared shell/theme, items/presets, registry metadata, Go DTOs,
frontend types, compatibility adapter, and drift checks are implemented and
verified. The remaining work is intentionally assigned to later phases:

- [x] **Phase 3:** consume `PageSection<T>` shell contracts at the page-builder
      boundary and consolidate every renderer family behind one shared
      `SectionFrame` while retaining the legacy save envelope.
- [x] **Phase 4:** add shadow normalized persistence, transactional projection,
      resumable backfill, quarantine, and content-free parity reporting.
- [x] **Phase 5:** invoke normalized decoding from typed mutation services and
      enforce transactional expected revisions/conflict responses.
- [x] **Phase 7:** define and exercise cutover flags, parity metrics, quarantine,
      rollback criteria, and cleanup gates.

### Phase 3 Closure

- [x] Extract the registered-section outer layout, spacing, background,
      animation, suspense, move, copy, and cut behavior from `BlockRenderer` into
      `SectionFrame` without changing the rendered DOM contract.
- [x] Add direct frame tests for legacy shell projection and movement context;
      keep all four renderer-family parity tests green.
- [x] Feed generated `SharedSectionShell` values into `SectionFrame` through the
      compatibility boundary and project shell edits back into the current
      document envelope without erasing unknown or section-specific config.
- [x] Remove duplicated shared toolbars from all 15 block implementations. The
      frame owns exactly one toolbar; the six renderer families with specialized
      commands portal only those type-specific actions into it.
- [x] Replace renderer dispatch casts with an exhaustive typed registry that
      owns each lazy component, generated version/default/capability metadata,
      and clipboard sanitizer. Unknown sections retain a safe framed fallback.
- [x] Add one shared appearance editor for container width, bounded content
      scale, background/text/`h1`/`h2`/`h3` color sources, and authored collapse
      settings, including inherit/literal/palette modes and contrast warnings.
- [x] Resolve page palette colors only through declared, validated, namespaced
      CSS variables and reject unsafe literal/declaration input at the frontend
      compatibility boundary; backend contract validation remains authoritative.
- [x] Apply scaling to an overflow-safe inner content wrapper, preserve reachable
      horizontal content, and keep toolbar controls outside the scaled region.
- [x] Implement an accessible `aria-expanded` collapse trigger. Viewer state is
      local and permission-aware, survives React rerenders, and resets when the
      page, section identity, or authoritative revision changes.
- [x] Preserve semantic heading/subheading placement and inline content editing
      inside renderers where DOM structure differs; `SectionFrame` owns shared
      presentation and actions, not a forced one-size-fits-all heading wrapper.

### Phase 4 Closure

- [x] Add idempotent fresh/incremental schema for page themes/tokens, section
      instances, palette references, section items, presets, responses,
      quarantine records, and parity runs under names that cannot collide with
      the dormant global `page_sections`/`page_items` tables.
- [x] Enforce page ownership, cascades, typed section discriminators, shell/config
      bounds, revisions, stable server IDs, page-scoped legacy key identity, item
      identity, response idempotency, and palette-token deletion restrictions.
- [x] Implement a bounded legacy-to-normalized projector for object/string config,
      numeric/string IDs, `features`, shell/config aliases, defaults, items,
      unknown-field quarantine, unsafe colors, and response-free interactive
      definitions. The reverse projector preserves the compatibility envelope.
- [x] Make ordinary page creates and builder updates refresh normalized shadow
      rows in the same transaction as authoritative `pages.content`; interactive
      record mutations remain document-owned until the Phase 6 sensitive migration.
- [x] Retain normalized section/item server IDs across reruns and reorders, remove
      stale rows transactionally, and preserve exact source ordering separately
      from display order.
- [x] Add safe operational telemetry containing hashes, counts, repair codes,
      quarantine field names, run counters, and mismatch codes without page
      content, answers, idempotency keys, or quarantined values.
- [x] Add `page-section-shadow-backfill`, an ID-ordered resumable command with a
      required batch size of 1-500; reruns are idempotent and report the next
      cursor plus matched/quarantined/mismatched counts.
- [x] Fix fresh-schema/rerun defects discovered by real PostgreSQL verification:
      provisioning baseline tables now precede their seed rows, the inbox group
      migration handles both legacy and fresh schemas, and store migrations 022
      and 023 use idempotent guards. Schema reruns also no longer reset an
      existing database role password to the deployment template placeholder.

The Phase 4 statement above records the then-current response authority. Phase 6
now owns the page-specific normalized response cutover described below.

### Phase 5 Closure

- [x] Add feature-gated typed section list/create/update/delete/reorder and page
      palette mutation endpoints. The gate is backend-owned and page-specific:
      `PAGE_TYPED_SECTION_MUTATIONS` must be enabled and the page's latest shadow
      parity status must be `matched`.
- [x] Enforce editor/owner/admin authorization through the centralized,
      fail-closed `PagePolicy.RequirePageEditor` service gate before normalized
      values reach the repository.
- [x] Decode section configs through the generated bounded duplicate-key-safe
      factory; validate shared shells, items, themes, safe colors, integration
      references, request size, identity, and field bounds without echoing config.
- [x] Lock the page and normalized rows in one transaction, require expected
      revisions, return content-free conflicts, preserve stable server IDs,
      converge different-section writes independently, and revision-guard
      structural reorders and palette replacements.
- [x] Rebuild `pages.content` transactionally after each typed definition write
      so old reads and rollback remain available. Interactive records never enter
      normalized section config, audit metadata, or WebSocket invalidations;
      Phase 6 moves matched pages to the dedicated response table while retaining
      the authorization-filtered rollback projection.
- [x] Reject whole-document definition changes on typed-ready pages while still
      allowing metadata-only legacy updates and retaining the legacy path for
      flag-disabled or non-matched pages.
- [x] Move `PageBuilder` to typed updates per page without changing renderer
      inputs. Debounced changes diff against the authoritative document;
      structural actions first flush queued edits; same-section `409` conflicts
      explain the reload instead of silently overwriting either editor.
- [x] Subscribe page views to `page:{id}`, target typed invalidations only to
      subscribers other than the HTTP sender, share/replay subscriptions across
      the singleton socket, and REST-refetch after reconnect to recover missed
      revisions.
- [x] Add migration 031 so page-theme token order swaps can use a deferred unique
      constraint while final page-scoped uniqueness and 0-63 bounds remain intact.

